    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-01T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-01T16:00:00-05:00" n="94"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/3162</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-01T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 1, 1917, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3351 Your numbers 4925,<note n="2" xml:id="d94fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_94">p. 94</ref>.</note>
                        4951,<note n="3" xml:id="d94fn3">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_96">p. 96</ref>.</note> and
                        4957.<note n="4" xml:id="d94fn4">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_97">p. 97</ref>.</note>
                    Department has only received from German Ambassador a note dated January
                        10,<note n="5" xml:id="d94fn5">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_82">p. 82</ref>.</note>
                    enclosing a memorandum calling attention to the reports from England of arming
                    of merchant vessels, particularly with guns at the bow, and mentioning certain
                    admiralty orders found on board French and Italian vessels, regarding use of
                    guns and giving a brief argument to show that the armed merchantmen of the
                    Allied, powers should be regarded and treated as warships even according to the
                    principles laid down in the American memorandum of March 25, 1916.<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d94fn6">
                        <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_244">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, Supplement, p.
                        244</ref>.</note> This Government has been considering the status of armed
                    ships and has not been in position to reply to this note. It received,
                    yesterday, the note declaring the submarine blockade of England which would seem
                    to make a reply now superfluous.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
